{{Infobox person | name = Dov Gottesman | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1929 | birth_place = | death_date = 22 February 2011 (age 82) | death_place = New York City | death_cause = | restingplace = | nationality = Israeli | residence = New York, London, Geneva and Tel Aviv | education = | alma mater = | occupation = art collector | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | known for = president, [[Israel Museum]], 2001-11 | boards = | salary = | networth = | spouse = Rachel Gottesman | children = Assaf, [[Noam Gottesman|Noam]] and Yoav | parents = | relations = | website = }}
'''Dov Gottesman''' (1929 - 22 February 2011) was an Israeli art collector, and president of the [[Israel Museum]] from 2001 until his death in 2011.
Dov Gottesman was born in 1929,<ref name="haaretz1"/> although this has also been incorrectly reported as 1917.<ref name="artasiapacific1">{{cite web|url=http://artasiapacific.com/News/DovGottesman19172011 |title=Dov Gottesman19172011 |publisher=ArtAsiaPacific |date=2011-03-22 |accessdate=2017-05-08}}</ref>
In 1996, Gottesman became chairman of the [[Israel Museum]], and in 2001, succeeded [[Teddy Kollek]] as president.<ref name="haaretz1">{{cite web|last=Alfon |first=Dov |url=http://www.haaretz.com/israel-museum-head-dov-gottesman-dies-at-82-1.345112 |title=Israel Museum head Dov Gottesman dies at 82 - Haaretz - Israel News |publisher=Haaretz.com |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2017-05-08}}</ref><ref name="nytimes1">{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E0D6113AF930A15751C0A9679D8B63 |title=Paid Notice - Deaths GOTTESMAN, DOV - Paid Death Notice - NYTimes.com |publisher=New York Times |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2017-05-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=123144 |title=Term details |publisher=British Museum |date= |accessdate=2017-05-08}}</ref>
Gottesman lived between New York, London, Geneva and Tel Aviv.<ref name="haaretz1"/>
He was married to Rachel, and they had three sons, Assaf, [[Noam Gottesman|Noam]] and Yoav.<ref name="haaretz1"/><ref name="nytimes1"/> He died on 22 February 2011, at his home in New York, aged 82.<ref name="artasiapacific1"/><ref name="haaretz1"/>
