'''''JamBase''''' is an [[online database]] and news portal of [[live music]] and [[music festival|festivals]] with a focus on [[jam bands]].<ref name=wired>{{cite web|last1=Greenwald|first1=Ted|title=Geeks to Music Industry: APIs Can Set You Free|url=https://www.wired.com/2009/12/geeks-to-music-industry-apis-can-set-you-free/|website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|accessdate=July 20, 2015}}</ref> It was founded by Andy Gadiel and Ted Kartzman in 1998.<ref>[http://www.hudsonreporter.com/view/full_story/2372555/article-Pump-up-the-jam-JamBase-Web-site-offers-the-ultimate-music-resource? "Pump up the jam JamBase Web site offers the ultimate music resource"]. ''Hudson Reporter'', by :JoAnne Steglitz Jul 03, 2001 </ref> The website primarily acts as a service, providing a public [[API]] that concert promoters and venues use to publish concert data to the site. The data is also used by third-party developers for other products. In addition to raw data, the website includes a news section publishing information about concerts in a blog format.<ref name=wired /><ref name=sfgate>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=James|title=Spreading the jam / Web site founded by and for fans of live music is a grassroots hit|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Spreading-the-jam-Web-site-founded-by-and-for-2858634.php|accessdate=July 20, 2015|work=[[San Francisco Gate]]|date=March 30, 2002}}</ref>

{{as of|June 2015}} ''JamBase'' ranks as the 4,945th most visited sites in the United States according to [[Alexa Internet|Alexa]], and 27,837th globally.<ref>{{cite web|title=jambase.com Site Overview|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/jambase.com|website=[[Alexa Internet|Alexa]]|accessdate=July 20, 2015}}</ref>

{{as of|October 2018}} JamBase's public API at http://api.jambase.com was disabled, as well as developer information at http://developer.jambase.com being removed without notice. No statement has been released by JamBase in regards to the public API's future. Currently both pages report a 596 "Service Not Found" error

