{{about|the note tool|the technology company|TinderBox Inc.|other uses|Tinderbox (disambiguation)}} {{ infobox software | name = Tinderbox | logo = | screenshot = | caption = | developer = [[Eastgate Systems]] | released = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2002}} | latest release version = 7.0 | latest release date = {{Start date and age|2017|02|24}} | operating system = [[Mac OS]], [[Mac OS X]] | platform = | genre = [[Content Management]], [[Outliner]], [[Personal information manager]] | license = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]] | website = {{url|www.eastgate.com/Tinderbox/}} }}
'''Tinderbox''' is a personal [[content management system]] and [[personal knowledge base]].
It is a tool for storing, arranging, exploring, and publishing data.<ref>[http://www.macworld.com/2004/05/reviews/minifinders8/ Minifinders: Multimedia to Organization Software], MacWorld, May 18, 2004. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050528225423/http://www.macworld.com/2004/05/reviews/minifinders8/ |date=May 28, 2005 }}</ref>
== Developer ==
Tinderbox was developed for [[Mac OS]] and [[Mac OS X]] by Mark Bernstein,<ref>[https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/03/interesting-software-update-tinderbox-how-to-jerrys-brain/387181/ Interesting Software Update: Tinderbox How-To, Jerry’s Brain - James Fallows] The Atlantic, 9 March 2015</ref> Chief Engineer of [[Eastgate Systems]].<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-107525662.html Tinderbox 1.2: multipurpose app sparks, stores, and shares ideas.], MacWorld, September 1, 2003. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516191154/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-107525662.html |date=May 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB106632803395183400?mod=googlewsj Hurrah For Great Mac Software] by Jeremy Wagstaff, The Wall Street Journal, October 16, 2003.</ref>
== Features ==
Its functions include storing and organizing notes, plans, and ideas, and sharing ideas through blogs.<ref>[http://www.eastgate.com/Tinderbox/ Eastgate Tinderbox product page, August 16, 2007]</ref>
It also offers functionality similar to that of outliner and spatial hypertext/[[mind mapping]] tools, in addition to knowledge management, database and agent(persistent search) tools.
Tinderbox is used for a wide variety of tasks:
* As a personal web publishing system, with good support for blog creation and management <ref>[http://www.eastgate.com/Tinderbox/Flint/ Flint]</ref> * Personal information management <ref>[http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=900077 Mark Bernstein, "Composites, Construction, Hypertext", Proceedings of the fourteenth ACM conference on Hypertext and hypermedia, ACM, New York, 2001. pp. 122-123.]</ref> * Outlining and [[mind mapping]] <ref>See the Tinderbox manual</ref> * [[Concept map]]ping * [[Note-taking]] <ref>[http://www.NotesAboutNotes.com/ Notes about Notes] and [http://notesaboutnotes.com/Notes/TinderboxPrototypes.html Tinderbox Prototypes]</ref> * Plot and story construction and writing<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-djSAmKbMQY</ref> * Creating hypertexts
